This class provides details on why current platform does not meet application platform requirements. Note that severe problems are reported immediately and therefore full check may be not performed and some (unrelated to fatal problem) methods may provide false positive answers.

If multiple components do not match then worst status is reported. Application need to repeat checks on each individual component if it want to find out all details. @class PlatformMismatchEvent @for dtjava

@method jreStatus @return {string} Returns "ok" if error was not due to missing JRE. Otherwise return error code characterizing the problem:
  • none - no JRE were detected on the system
  • old - some version of JRE was detected but it does not match platform requirements
  • oldplugin - matching JRE found but it is configured to use deprecated Java plugin that does not support Java applets

      canAutoInstall() and isRelaunchNeeded() can be used to get more details on how seamless user' install experience will be.

@method javafxStatus @return {string} Returns "ok" if error was not due to missing JavaFX. Otherwise return error code characterizing the problem:
  • none - no JavaFX runtime is detected on the system
  • old - some version of JavaFX runtime iss detected but it does not match platform requirements
  • disabled - matching JavaFX is detected but it is disabled
  • unsupported - JavaFX is not supported on this platform

      canAutoInstall() and isRelaunchNeeded() can be used to get more details on how seamless user' install experience will be.

The Java Deployment Toolkit is utility to deploy Java content in the browser as applets or applications using right version of Java. If needed it can initiate upgrade of user's system to install required components of Java platform.

Note that some of Deployment Toolkit methods may not be fully operational if used before web page body is loaded (because DT native plugins could not be instantiated). If you intend to use it before web page DOM tree is ready then dtjava.js needs to be loaded inside the body element of the page and before use of other DT APIs. @class dtjava @static

Helper function: cross-browser onLoad support

This will call fn() once document is loaded. If page is already loaded when this method is called then fn() is called immediately.

If strictMode is true then fn() is called once page and all its assets are loaded (i.e. when document ready state will be 'complete'). Otherwise fn() is called after DOM tree is fully created (but some assets may not yet be loaded).

It is ok to call this function multiple times. It will append to existing chain of events (and do not replace them). @method addOnloadCallback @param {function} fn (required) function to call @param strictMode {boolean} Flag indicating whether page assets need to be loaded before launch (default is false).

Platform requirements for application launch.


The version pattern strings are of the form #[.#[.#[_#]]][+|*], which includes strings such as "1.6", * "2.0*", and "1.6.0_18+".

A star (*) means "any version within this family" where family is defined by prefix and a plus (+) means "any version greater or equal to the specified version". For example "1.6.0*" matches 1.6.0_25 but not 1.7.0_01, whereas "1.6.0+" or "1.*" match both.

If the version pattern does not include all four version components but does not end with a star or plus, it will be treated as if it ended with a star. "2.0" is exactly equivalent to "2.0*", and will match any version number beginning with "2.0".

Null version string is treated as "there is no requirement to have it installed". Validation will pass whether this component is installed or not.

Both "+" and "*" will match any installed version of component. However if component is not installed then validation will fail. @class Platform @for dtjava @constructor @param r {array} Array describing platform requirements. Element names should match Platform properties.

Callback to be called to obtain content of the splash panel. Gets application launch descriptor as an input. If null is returned then splash is disabled. Non-null return value is expected to be html snippet to be added into splash overlay. Only applicable to embed().

Note that autohiding splash is not supported by all platforms. Splash will be hidden by default for JavaFX application but not for Swing/AWT applets. In later case if use of splash is desirable then app need to call dtjava.hideSplash() explicitly to initiate hiding splash. @property onGetSplash @type function(app) @default Default splash panel for JavaFX applications embedded into web page, null otherwise.

Called if embedding or launching application need additional components to be installed. This callback is responsible for handling such situation, e.g. reporting need to install something to the user, initiating installation using install() and hiding splash panel for embedded apps (if needed). After installation is complete callback implementation may retry attempt to launch application using provided launch function.

This method is NOT called if platform requirement could not be met (e.g. if platfrom is not supported or if installation is not possible).

Default handler provides "click to install" solution for embedded application and attempt to perform installation without additional questions for apps started using launch().

If handler is null then it is treated as no op handler.

Parameters:

  • app - application launch descriptor. For embedded applications app.placeholder will refer to the root of the applet area in the DOM tree (to be used for visual feedback)
  • platform - application platform requirements
  • cb - set of callbacks to be used during installation process
  • isAutoinstall - true if install can be launched automatically
  • needRestart - true if browser restart will be required once installation is complete
  • launchFunction - function to be executed to retry launching the application once installation is finished
@property onInstallNeeded @type function(app, platform, cb, isAutoinstall, needRelaunch, launchFunc) @default Default implementation shows "click to install" banner for embedded applications or initiates installation immediately for applications launched from web page.

Called before installation of required component is triggered. For manual install scenario it is called before installation page is opened.

This method can be used to provide visual feedback to the user during the installation. Placeholder points to the area that can be used for visualization, for embedded applications it will be applet area. If null then callee need to find place for visualization on its own.

In case of automatic launch of installation onInstallFinished will be called once installation is complete (succesfully or not).

If handler is null then it is treated as no-op handler. Parameters:

  • placeholder - DOM element to insert visual feedback into. If null then callee need to add visual feedback to the document on its own (e.g. placeholder will be null if installation is not happening in context of embedding application into web page).
  • component - String "Java", "JavaFX" or "Java bundle"
  • isAutoInstall - true if installer will be launched automatically
  • restartNeeded - boolean to specify whether browser restart will be required
@property onInstallStarted @type function(placeholder, component, isAuto, restartNeeded) @default No-op

Called once installation of required component is completed. This method will NOT be called if installation is performed in manual mode. Parameters:
  • placeholder - DOM element that was passed to onInstallStarted to insert visual feedback into.
  • component - String "jre" or "javafx"
  • status - status code is string categorizing the status of install. ("success", "error:generic", "error:download" or "error:canceled")
  • relaunchNeeded - boolean to specify whether browser restart is required to complete the installation
@property onInstallFinished @type function(placeholder, component, status, relaunchNeeded) @default no op

This function is called if application can not be deployed because current platform does not match given platform requirements. It is also called if request to install missing components can not be completed due to platform.

Problem can be fatal error or transient issue (e.g. relaunch needed). Further details can be extracted from provided mismatchEvent. Here are some typical combinations:

  • Current browser is not supported by Java - (r.isUnsupportedBrowser())
  • Browser need to be restarted before application can be launched - (r.isRelaunchNeeded())
  • JRE specific codes
    • JRE is not supported on this platform - (r.jreStatus() == "unsupported")
    • JRE is not detected and need to be installed - (r.jreStatus() == "none")
    • Installed version of JRE does not match requirements - (r.jreStatus() == "old")
    • Matching JRE is detected but deprecated Java plugin is used and it does not support JNLP applets - (r.jreStatus() == "oldplugin")
  • JavaFX specific codes
    • JavaFX is not supported on this platform - (r.javafxStatus() == "unsupported")
    • JavaFX Runtime is missing and need to be installed manually - (r.javafxStatus() == "none")
    • Installed version of JavaFX Runtime does not match requirements - (r.javafxStatus() == "old")
    • JavaFX Runtime is installed but currently disabled - (r.javafxStatus() == "disabled")
Default error handler handles both application launch errors and embedded content. @property onDeployError @type function(app, mismatchEvent)

* returns true if we can enable DT plugin auto-install without chance of
     * deadlock on cert mismatch dialog
     *
     * requestedJREVersion param is optional - if null, it will be
     * treated as installing any JRE version
     *
     * DT plugin for 6uX only knows about JRE installer signed by SUN cert.
     * If it encounter Oracle signed JRE installer, it will have chance of
     * deadlock when running with IE.  This function is to guard against this.
